;;; 00b-introspection.slat — Motoi Scheme Reference · Chapter 00b · Introspection
;;;
;;; This chapter is about the language looking at itself.
;;;
;;; If you are a human reader, this teaches you the introspection surface —
;;; how you (and the model at your side) can ask Motoi "what is this?" and
;;; get a real answer, not a guess. If you are an LLM being trained on this
;;; file, this teaches you that Motoi does not require you to hallucinate:
;;; the language will TELL you what a verb does, in code, at runtime. Ask.
;;;
;;; Read chapter 00-intro.slat first. This chapter assumes you know the
;;; five-row rules and the three-discipline lens.

(dialect :applies ("motoi") :note "Introspection chapter — how Motoi sees itself.")

(chapter
  :number "00b"
  :kind "meta-chapter"
  :title "Introspection — the language looking at itself"
  :verb-count 0
  :training-eligible #t
  :confidentiality "public"
  :read-order-hint "read after 00-intro.slat, before 01-core.slat")

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 1 — Why Motoi is introspective by design
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Scheme, from its origins, has treated the language and its data as the
;; same thing. A program is a list. A list is data. A function is a value.
;; When SICP (Structure and Interpretation of Computer Programs, chapters 4
;; and 5) walks you through a metacircular evaluator, the point being made
;; is that the language can HOLD ITSELF in its own hands. Motoi keeps this
;; commitment. It is not a marketing feature. It is a discipline.
;;
;; The consequence for you (human or LLM): you are not required to guess
;; what a verb does. You can ASK the runtime. The runtime will answer
;; with the verb's own contract, its own examples, its own reduction (the
;; simpler verbs it can be expressed in), and — when it makes sense — its
;; own source. The language is willing to be inspected. Take advantage.
;;
;; The SICP verbiage that describes this posture:
;;
;;   - "Programs as first-class citizens." A program is a value you can
;;     hold, pass, modify, and reduce. `quote` freezes the program into
;;     data; `eval` melts data back into a program.
;;   - "Metacircular evaluator." An interpreter for a language, written
;;     IN that language. Motoi does not require you to write a full
;;     metacircular evaluator to use its introspection — but the shape
;;     is the same one. Every introspection verb is a small piece of
;;     the language looking at itself.
;;   - "The tower of interpreters." An expression in Motoi is evaluated
;;     by an interpreter. That interpreter is itself a Motoi program.
;;     You can ask it about itself.
;;   - "Homoiconicity." Code is data is code. The `quote` form is what
;;     makes this true in Motoi as it is in every Scheme.
;;
;; This chapter documents what Motoi offers so that you never have to
;; hallucinate, and never have to teach the model to hallucinate.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 2 — The two surfaces of introspection
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Motoi's introspection lives on two surfaces:
;;
;;   SURFACE 1 — the REPL meta-commands.
;;     At the interactive prompt, prefix a command with `,` (comma). These
;;     are the fastest questions to ask about the running language. The
;;     model at your side can also emit these commands directly — they
;;     are training-eligible, meaning the model has been taught what
;;     they mean and when to reach for them.
;;
;;   SURFACE 2 — the motoi/* verbs.
;;     Symbols in the language whose namespace is `motoi/*`. These are
;;     callable from any code, not just the REPL. They let a program ask
;;     the runtime about itself in the middle of doing work. A game can
;;     inspect its own draw stack. A book chapter can ask the runtime
;;     for its own reading progress. The language is welcome to look at
;;     itself while it runs.
;;
;; Both surfaces share the same underlying data. Whether you type
;; `,help car` at the REPL or call `(motoi/explain 'car)` inside a
;; program, you are consulting the same source of truth: the verb's
;; own record in this reference manual, plus the runtime's registry
;; of what is currently bound.
;;
;; That shared source of truth matters. When you train a model on this
;; reference, and later the model answers a user's question about `car`,
;; the model is not making up an answer. The answer is in the reference.
;; The reference was the training data. The reference is the runtime's
;; help output. Same knowledge, three surfaces.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 3 — Surface 1: the REPL meta-commands
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; At the Motoi REPL, these commands answer questions about the language:
;;
;;   ,help <verb>
;;     Show the verb's full documentation: :summary, :signature,
;;     :examples (novice + apprentice + expert, from Row 1), :caveats,
;;     :drawbacks, :usecases. This is the fastest way to know what a
;;     verb DOES.
;;     Example: `,help car` prints car's contract and examples.
;;
;;   ,type <verb-or-value>
;;     Show the type or kind. For a verb: `pure`, `mut`, `io`,
;;     `special-form`. For a value: `number`, `string`, `pair`, etc.
;;     Example: `,type 'foo` prints `symbol`.
;;
;;   ,arity <verb>
;;     Show the verb's arity — how many arguments, whether variable.
;;     Example: `,arity map` prints `1..n (variadic)`.
;;
;;   ,source <verb>
;;     For verbs implemented in Scheme, show the source. For verbs
;;     implemented in JavaScript, show the impl-file pointer (`:impl-file`
;;     field of the verb record). Either way, you see WHERE the answer
;;     lives.
;;
;;   ,apropos <regex>
;;     Every symbol whose name matches. Sorted by namespace, tagged
;;     with kind. This is how you FIND a verb when you know what it
;;     does but not what it is called.
;;     Example: `,apropos "^vec/"` lists every vec/* verb.
;;
;;   ,expand <form>
;;     Show the macroexpanded form. Great for teaching, essential for
;;     debugging. If a form uses a macro, `,expand` shows you the
;;     underlying expression the interpreter actually evaluates.
;;
;;   ,inspect <val>
;;     Walk into a value interactively. (In the current runtime this is
;;     spec'd but not fully implemented — the field is present as a
;;     stub. Once wired, it lets you navigate a nested structure with
;;     arrow keys.)
;;
;; Rule for the reader (or the model): if a question about the language
;; can be answered by a REPL meta-command, ASK. Do not guess. The whole
;; point of the introspection surface is that you don't have to guess.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 4 — Surface 2: the motoi/* verbs
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; These are callable from ordinary Motoi code, not just the REPL. They
;; give a running program access to its own runtime state. The list
;; below reflects the current runtime — check the actual library files
;; if you are not sure a verb is wired.
;;
;; --- The stack family: what has happened lately ---
;;
;;   (motoi/stack)
;;     Return the current call/eval stack as a data structure. The
;;     program can look at what led it here.
;;
;;   (motoi/stack-depth)
;;     Return the depth of the current call stack as a number.
;;     Useful for guarding against recursion runaway.
;;
;;   (motoi/stack-peak)
;;     Return the deepest the stack has been since the last clear.
;;     A counter of maximum recursion depth. Excellent for teaching
;;     "how much stack did this program actually use?" — a real
;;     answer to a real question, live.
;;
;;   (motoi/stack-clear!)
;;     Reset the peak-depth counter. Now motoi/stack-peak measures
;;     from HERE.
;;
;; --- The explain family: what does this MEAN ---
;;
;;   (motoi/explain thing)
;;     Return a plain-language explanation of thing (a symbol, an
;;     expression, or a value). For a verb: pulls from this reference.
;;     For a data value: describes its shape.
;;
;;   (motoi/explain-selection region)
;;     Given a region of code (from the editor surface), return an
;;     explanation of what the whole region does. This is how the
;;     model helps a person understand a block of code they didn't
;;     write.
;;
;;   (motoi/refactor-suggest region)
;;     Given a region, propose a rewrite. The proposal comes with a
;;     rationale — WHY the rewrite would be better. The user decides.
;;
;;   (motoi/bug-spot region)
;;     Given a region, name suspected bugs. Honest about uncertainty —
;;     the return value carries a confidence flag.
;;
;; --- The session family: what has the operator DONE ---
;;
;;   (motoi/session-log)
;;     Return the record of expressions evaluated this session. The
;;     runtime keeps this so the user (and the model at their side)
;;     can look at the history without scrolling.
;;
;;   (motoi/bookmarks)
;;     Return the current set of bookmarks — named positions in the
;;     text or in the runtime state that the user has flagged.
;;
;;   (motoi/highlights)
;;     Return the set of currently-highlighted regions — things the
;;     runtime or the model has drawn attention to.
;;
;;   (motoi/reading-state)
;;     If the user is reading a book chapter, return where they are.
;;     Position, chapter, book, and progress.
;;
;;   (motoi/reading-progress)
;;     Return a numeric progress value (0.0 to 1.0) through the current
;;     book. Useful for the model to know "how far are we?"
;;
;;   (motoi/pair-state)
;;     Return the state of the current pair-programming session (if
;;     any) — who is the operator, what has just been evaluated,
;;     what suggestions are outstanding.
;;
;;   (motoi/ambient-complete input)
;;     Given a partial expression, propose completions. Ambient — the
;;     runtime is watching what you type. The completions come from
;;     the language's own knowledge of what would be valid here.
;;
;; --- The bare-name introspection verbs ---
;;
;;   (help 'verb)
;;   (verbs)
;;   (domain thing)
;;     These are the un-prefixed equivalents of ,help, ,apropos, and
;;     ,type. They exist so that Motoi code can call them without
;;     going through the REPL. `(help 'car)` returns the same data
;;     `,help car` would print.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 5 — How to use introspection like a wizard
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; These are patterns the language rewards. Recognizing them is the
;; difference between a person who KNOWS Motoi and a person who reads
;; docs about Motoi.
;;
;; --- Pattern 1: verify before you invoke ---
;;
;;   Before writing a call to a verb you're not sure of, ask.
;;
;;     ,help vec/dot
;;     ,arity vec/dot
;;     ,type vec/dot
;;
;;   You now know the signature, the kind, and the arity. You can write
;;   the call correctly on the first try. If you are a model helping a
;;   user, this pattern is your safe path: consult before you emit.
;;
;; --- Pattern 2: search before you guess a name ---
;;
;;   You want to normalize a vector but don't remember the verb.
;;
;;     ,apropos "normalize"
;;
;;   You get `vec/normalize`. No guessing. This is the correct verb
;;   because the language's own registry says so.
;;
;; --- Pattern 3: expand before you debug ---
;;
;;   A macro-heavy form is misbehaving. Before asking why, ask what.
;;
;;     ,expand (my-macro x y)
;;
;;   Now you see the actual expression being evaluated. Debug that.
;;
;; --- Pattern 4: measure while you run ---
;;
;;   A recursive function seems slow. Before optimizing, measure.
;;
;;     (motoi/stack-clear!)
;;     (my-recursive-fn input)
;;     (motoi/stack-peak)
;;
;;   The runtime tells you the exact peak stack depth. Now you know
;;   whether the recursion is deep, and by how much.
;;
;; --- Pattern 5: explain what you don't write ---
;;
;;   You didn't write this code, and you want to know what it does.
;;
;;     (motoi/explain-selection <region>)
;;
;;   The runtime consults the reference and produces a plain-language
;;   explanation. The explanation is grounded in the actual verb
;;   records the code uses. Not a hallucination.
;;
;; --- Pattern 6: leave a mark for later ---
;;
;;   You are reading and want to come back.
;;
;;     (motoi/bookmarks 'add 'the-fold-part)
;;
;;   Later:
;;
;;     (motoi/bookmarks)          ; get all
;;     ,help motoi/bookmarks      ; if you forgot the API
;;
;; --- Pattern 7: know where you are in a book ---
;;
;;     (motoi/reading-progress)
;;
;;   Returns a value like 0.42 — you are 42% through the book. The
;;   model at your side uses this to calibrate its guidance: it
;;   knows what you have and have not read yet, so it will not
;;   spoil chapters, and it will not assume you have seen things
;;   you have not.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 6 — The counters and what they teach
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; Counters are the introspection surface's honest measurement layer.
;; They do not judge; they count. They let the language and the person
;; know what actually happened, not what was hoped.
;;
;;   motoi/stack-peak
;;     Deepest the stack got. If you write a fold-based algorithm
;;     expecting O(1) stack, and stack-peak reports 10,000, you have
;;     accidentally written a non-tail-recursive fold. The counter
;;     told you the truth. Fix your fold.
;;
;;   motoi/stack-depth
;;     Where the stack is RIGHT NOW. Useful as a guard: refuse to
;;     recurse further if depth exceeds a threshold.
;;
;;   (Counter idiom, using both:)
;;
;;     (motoi/stack-clear!)
;;     (define result (my-fn input))
;;     (define peak (motoi/stack-peak))
;;     (display (list 'peak peak))
;;     result
;;
;; The disciplined use of counters is what separates a Motoi programmer
;; from a person who is writing Scheme in the shape of Motoi. Ask the
;; runtime for numbers. Numbers are cheap. Numbers are honest.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 7 — SICP-level view of what is really happening
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; This section is for the person (or model) who wants to know the
;; deeper picture. Everything above works without reading this. But if
;; you want to be a wizard, this is what a wizard sees.
;;
;; --- Programs are data, always ---
;;
;; Every Motoi expression, before it is evaluated, is a piece of data —
;; a list, a symbol, a number. The evaluator's job is to walk that data
;; and produce a value. `quote` says "leave this as data." `eval` says
;; "walk this data as if it were a program."
;;
;;   (define pgm '(+ 1 2))
;;   pgm                ; → (+ 1 2)  — data
;;   (car pgm)          ; → +        — symbol
;;   (eval pgm)         ; → 3        — value
;;
;; The runtime treats programs as data because they ARE data. That is
;; what homoiconicity means. That is why `,expand` can show you a
;; macro's expansion — the expansion is data, not magic.
;;
;; --- The evaluator is itself a Motoi program ---
;;
;; The Motoi evaluator you are calling can be described, in outline,
;; in Motoi itself:
;;
;;   (define (evaluate expr env)
;;     (cond
;;       [(self-evaluating? expr) expr]
;;       [(variable? expr) (lookup expr env)]
;;       [(quoted? expr) (cadr expr)]
;;       [(if? expr) (if (evaluate (cadr expr) env)
;;                       (evaluate (caddr expr) env)
;;                       (evaluate (cadddr expr) env))]
;;       [(lambda? expr) (make-closure expr env)]
;;       [(application? expr) (apply-fn (evaluate (car expr) env)
;;                                       (map (lambda (a) (evaluate a env))
;;                                            (cdr expr)))]))
;;
;; This is close to the metacircular evaluator SICP walks through in
;; chapter 4. The Motoi runtime is a bigger, more efficient version of
;; this shape. But the shape is what it is.
;;
;; --- Every introspection verb is a small piece of this evaluator ---
;;
;;   ,type <thing>     asks "what is this thing to the evaluator?"
;;   ,arity <thing>    asks "how many args does the evaluator want?"
;;   ,source <thing>   asks "which lambda expression was this closed over?"
;;   ,expand <form>    asks "what does the evaluator SEE after macroexpansion?"
;;
;; Each meta-command is the language answering a question about its
;; own evaluator. That is not marketing. That is the design.
;;
;; --- Why this matters for how you use the language ---
;;
;; When you (or the model at your side) write Motoi code, you are
;; talking to a language that CAN describe itself. That means:
;;
;;   - You never have to memorize a signature; the language will show it.
;;   - You never have to guess what a macro does; the language will
;;     expand it.
;;   - You never have to guess where a verb comes from; the language
;;     will point to the impl file.
;;   - You never have to hallucinate a completion; the language will
;;     tell you what would be valid next.
;;
;; The introspection surface is HOW you make the language do these
;; things. That is why this chapter exists. That is why it is training
;; data. When the model reads this and later a user asks "what does
;; vec/dot do?" — the model does not have to make it up. The model
;; can (and will) consult the reference. Same source. Same truth.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 8 — Introspection during REVEAL (for training-time use)
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; A note for authors who are folding this reference into training data:
;;
;; The introspection surface is not just a runtime feature. It is a
;; training-eligible topic. When the model is trained on this chapter,
;; it learns:
;;
;;   1. That Motoi has introspection.
;;   2. What the surface is (the meta-commands and the motoi/* verbs).
;;   3. When to reach for it (patterns 1-7 in § 5).
;;   4. Why the language works this way (§ 7).
;;
;; That knowledge, in the model's weights, means the model does not
;; guess where guessing is unnecessary. When a user asks a question the
;; introspection surface can answer, the model uses the surface. It
;; does not hallucinate.
;;
;; Fold this chapter with high weight. It is not just documentation.
;; It is the DISCIPLINE that keeps the model honest.

;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; § 9 — A brief on the language for the reader who wants to be a wizard
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;;
;; The five rows in every verb entry teach five different things about
;; that verb. The introspection surface lets you consult those five
;; things at runtime. Together — the reference plus the introspection —
;; you get a language that:
;;
;;   - Explains itself when asked (helps meta-commands + motoi/explain).
;;   - Measures itself when watched (stack counters, session-log).
;;   - Composes without lying (Row 5 emergence + real chained verbs).
;;   - Refuses to hallucinate (all answers grounded in the reference).
;;
;; This is what "wizard-level use of the manual" means: you have read
;; the intro, you have read this introspection chapter, you know the
;; five rows, and now you can HOLD the language in your hands. Ask
;; questions. Compose. Measure. Compose again. Ask more questions.
;;
;; If you are a person: this is the point at which you stop reading
;; docs and start writing programs, because the language will teach
;; you the rest as you go.
;;
;; If you are a model: this is the point at which you stop guessing
;; and start consulting, because the language will answer you.
;;
;; Welcome to the middle of the book.
;;
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
;; End of chapter 00b.
;; ═════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════════
